Working with annual air quality data with the {tidyverse}

Published

December 13, 2022

Abstract
Much of openair is set up to work with hourly data from a small handful of sites. However, openair also makes it easy to access summary statistics for whole networks. In this document, the power of R and the tidyverse is demonstrated to analyse these large data sets. 
library(openair)
library(tidyverse)

1 Import Data

To import annual data, we use the âdata_typeâ argument in the various import*() functions. As weâre working in the tidyverse, lets make sure our data is tidy by using the âto_narrowâ argument as well. An additional step is also labelling each network with a column of its name, so they can be distinguished later.

Note that, when âdata_typeâ is âannualâ, the import*() function ignores arguments like âsiteâ and âpollutantâ.

The last step is to use bind_rows() from dplyr to combine all of the data frames together into one.

# import annual averages from all networks
aurn <-
  importAURN(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "AURN")

aqen <-
  importAQE(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "AQE")

saqn <-
  importSAQN(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "SAQN")

waqn <-
  importWAQN(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "WAQN")

niaq <-
  importNI(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "NIAQN")

lmam <-
  importLocal(
    year = 2018,
    data_type = "annual",
    to_narrow = TRUE,
    meta = TRUE
  ) %>% mutate(network = "Local")

# bind them together
all_aq <- bind_rows(aurn, aqen, saqn, waqn, niaq, lmam)

# clear up global environment
rm(aurn, aqen, saqn, waqn, niaq, lmam)

# preview
summary(all_aq)

There can be overlap between the different networks (for example, sites in the AURN can also be in the SAQN) so it may be appropriate to have a version of this dataset without these duplicates. The distinct() function is helpful here. We can specify a small number of columns, and distinct() will find unique combinations of them and return one row of the data per unique combination of these columns. â.keep_allâ retains the rest of the row.

all_distinct <- distinct(all_aq, site, species, date, .keep_all = TRUE)

2 Network Average Statistics

A first question to ask may be âhow do the networks differ in terms of statistical summaries?â. You could use summary() for this, but this just returns an unstructured list of values. Lets use dplyr to get a data frame, which we can then use for further analysis.

Lets use the data frame with duplicates, as thatâll treat every network totally individually.

Our first step could be to set a certain data capture threshold. Lets say we need at least 80%. Then we can group_by() the ânetworkâ and âspeciesâ column and calculate some summary statistics.

network_stats <-
  all_aq %>%
  filter(data_capture > .8) %>%
  group_by(network, species) %>%
  summarise(min = min(value),
            mean = mean(value),
            median = median(value),
            max = max(value))

Lets compare NO2 concentrations for each network. Here we can see that the AURN is the most âextremeâ in that it has the widest range of values, although its mean is fairly low compared to other networks.

network_stats %>%
  filter(species == "no2")

3 Summaries by Site Type

A natural next question may be â is the AURN so low because it has a load of rural background sites in it, whereas the other networks (particularly local networks) are more focused on measuring in urban environments where more people live? Lets revisit our summary and group by site type as well.

stats_site_type <-
  all_aq %>%
  filter(data_capture > .8) %>%
  group_by(network, species, site_type) %>%
  summarise(q25 = quantile(value, na.rm = TRUE, .25),
            mean = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE),
            median = median(value, na.rm = TRUE),
            q75 = quantile(value, na.rm = TRUE, .75),
            n = n()) %>%
  filter(species == "no2")

This is a lot of data, so it may be a good idea to visualise it. openair doesnât have the functionality to create a bar chart, but ggplot2 does! FigureÂ 1 is a demonstration of a bar chart in ggplot2 without any finesse or fancy themes. The local networks are the highest on average, perhaps as local networks are the most targeted at high-polluting areas.

stats_site_type %>%
  filter(site_type %in% c("Rural Background", "Urban Background", "Urban Traffic")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = network, y = mean)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(site_type),
             scales = "free_x",
             space = "free_x")

For more general interest, FigureÂ 2 shows a nicer version of the same plot. This is mainly to demonstrate the fine control one can have over plots when using a flexible plotting system like ggplot2, so donât worry if you donât understand even half of whatâs written below!

stats_site_type %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(site_type %in% c("Rural Background", "Urban Background", "Urban Traffic")) %>%
  mutate(network = fct_reorder(network, mean)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = network, y = mean)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = network == "AURN"), show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymax = q75, ymin = q25)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0("n=", n), y = -2.5), size = 3) +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(site_type),
             scales = "free_x",
             space = "free_x") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = .5, hjust = 1),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()) +
  labs(y = quickText("Mean Annual NO2 (ug/m3)"),
       x = NULL) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("grey75", "hotpink"))

Summary statistics are okay, but they can often hide interesting nuances in the data. Lets instead consider the distribution of annual means. This shows that, while the AURN is in the middle of the networks as far as averages are concerned, it does have at least one large outlier site that rivals the local networks.

all_aq %>%
  filter(data_capture > .8,
         species == "no2",
         site_type == "Urban Traffic") %>%
  mutate(network = fct_reorder(network, value)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = network, x = value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(y = NULL, x = quickText("Annual NO2 (ug/m3)"))

4 Multiple pollutants

We could choose to examine multiple pollutants at once, such as through a scatter plot (FigureÂ 4). It is clear that sites with higher ozone typically have lower nitrogen dioxide, and vice-versa.

scatter_data <- 
  all_distinct %>%
  # filter dc/species
  filter(data_capture > .8,
         species %in% c("no2", "o3")) %>%
  # select needed columns
  select(site_type, site, species, value) %>%
  # reshape
  pivot_wider(names_from = species, values_from = value) %>%
  # drop missing
  drop_na(no2, o3) %>%
  # lump site types together
  mutate(site_type = fct_lump_n(site_type, n = 3))

scatter_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = no2, y = o3)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = site_type)) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = c(.8, .8)) +
  labs(y = quickText("Annual O3 (ug/m3)"),
       x = quickText("Annual NO2 (ug/m3)"),
       color = "Site Type")

R is a language built for statistics, so its really easy to examine this relationship in a more robust, statistical way. For example, we could quickly fit a linear model to examine how NO2 and O3 are related. We can see that, for every extra 1 unit of NO2, O3 drops by around 0.6 units. The linear model also explains around 76% of the variance in the data.

mod <- lm(o3 ~ no2, scatter_data)

summary(mod)

With some more knowledge of statistics, we can learn more information about this relationship. For example, when we add site type to our model, we can see that the nitrogen dioxide-ozone relationship is not significantly different for different site types (P >= 0.05) with the exception of urban traffic.

mod_sites <- lm(o3 ~ no2 * site_type, scatter_data)
summary(mod_sites)

We can actually plot this linear model on our graph quite easily. This very clearly shows the similarity between different site types, again with the exception of urban traffic for which the gradient is visually shallower likely owing to some outliers.

scatter_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = no2, y = o3)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = site_type)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = site_type), se = FALSE, method = "lm") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = c(.8, .8)) +
  labs(y = quickText("Annual O3 (ug/m3)"),
       x = quickText("Annual NO2 (ug/m3)"),
       color = "Site Type")

5 Geographic distributions

Another way to treat this data is by mapping it. One of the easiest ways to do this is through the leaflet package (not part of the tidyverse) which is demonstrated in FigureÂ 6. This could be described as a âspot concentrationâ map, which shows the distribution of different annual ozone concentrations.

library(leaflet)

map_data <- 
  all_distinct %>%
  filter(data_capture > .8,
         species == "o3")

pal <- colorNumeric(viridis::turbo(n = 100), domain = map_data$value)

leaflet(map_data) %>%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %>%
  addCircleMarkers(color = ~ pal(value), 
                   label = ~ site,
                   popup = ~ str_glue("Ozone: {value} ug/m3"),
                   radius = 2) %>%
  addLegend(pal = pal,
            values = map_data$value,
            title = "O<sub>3</sub>")
